latestIgtvVideos.title: Haircare Routine: Wavy 2A/2B Hair // Juicy Waves Routine // December ’20
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
My updated #haircare routine, explained in detail! My hair is wavy, and I follow a loose version of the CG Method.

I also want to touch upon something regarding the much-dreaded phenomenon, #FRIZZ.
The results I’ve achieved in this video are pretty low on frizz, but full disclosure: that’s in large part thanks to the fact that it’s currently winter, and so the humidity is relatively low. I do manage to minimise frizz thanks to the way I dry my hair, but even then, there is definitely some visible frizz to my hair when it’s summer or monsoon. And guess what? THAT’S OKAY! So if your hair still has some frizz even with proper care, please don’t freak out, it’s normal! No one can have zero frizz all the time.

A few additional details about the ARATA products that I’ve featured in this video:

- They do not feel sticky at all, and are easy to work with as they’re water soluble.

- A little goes a very long way, especially with the hair cream, so I think the value for money is excellent.

- The only con with these products, particularly the hair cream, is that the fragrance is rather strong. However, I find that it dissipates after a couple of hours, so it doesn’t really bother me.

Let me know in the comments below if you’d be interested in a more detailed review of these two styling products! And don’t forget to tell me about your favourite hair products and techniques too. 🌸

What are some things influencers say or do that annoy you? 🤭

#influencerdiaries #reelhooks #beautyinfluencers

No, they don’t cause cancer 🤦🏽‍♀️

WHY PARABENS DON’T NEED TO BE AVOIDED

- Parabens were developed in the 1920s and are still some of the most widely used preservatives in cosmetics. They’ve been safe use for over a century!
- They prevent a wide range of microbes (fungi, bacteria, etc.) from growing in your products.
- They’re effective even in very small quantities, meaning we’re barely exposed to any parabens even if they’re in stuff we use everyday. 
- The only health concern with parabens that is scientifically backed with data is allergy, which occurs in a VERY SMALL fraction of people, and usually on broken skin. 
- Avoiding parabens has led to brands using less effective and less understood preservatives (or avoiding them altogether), leading to moldy products which are a health risk.

SO WHY DO PEOPLE SAY PARABENS ARE BAD?

A 1998 study reported that parabens have weak estrogenic effects in rats. However, the parabens tested were found to be THOUSANDS TO MILLIONS OF TIMES WEAKER than the naturally occurring female sex hormone. In addition, these studies injected the parabens under rats’ skin, which is not the same as applying topical products. 

A 2004 study reported that they found parabens in 20 human breast tumours. This pushed parabens to the forefront of discussion, putting it on the “Dirty Dozen” list. Environmental groups called for a ban on it, and it even got banned in Denmark in 2011. However, there were tons of issues with this study:
- There was no control. They didn’t compare the cancer tissue containing parabens with healthy, non-cancerous tissue. If parabens had been found in non-cancerous tissue too, it would show that parabens aren’t linked to cancer. 
- Parabens were found even in samples without any tissue, suggesting that their equipment was already contaminated before tissue samples were tested. It’s possible that none of the parabens found even came from the breast tissue they tested!
- 6mo later, the researchers published a follow-up that their study doesn’t claim that parabens cause breast cancer, but the damage was done.

There’s more info you can read on labmuffin.com.

PARABENS ARE YOUR FRIENDS! #parabenfreeskincare

It’s giving the toddler mixing up their mom’s beauty products energy 😭

This new L’Oréal Paris Serum Tint’s formula is worth the hype, imo. It has light to medium buildable coverage, is transfer-proof, and lasts excellently all day even in the summer heat 💯 

Shade 4-5 Medium is the closest match for me, and 5-6 Medium Tan works well as a corrector + tint for areas where I have hyperpigmentation. 

#InfallibleInMyTint #TintedSerum #SkinTint #LOrealParisIndia #LOrealParis

1️⃣ Dark underarms are shameful or ugly
Nah girl. I’ve gotten quite a few hate comments for my dark underarms being visible in videos, but I refuse to hide them. Many brown people have dark underarms and there’s nothing wrong with it. Stop making people feel ashamed about their bodies. 

2️⃣ Parabens, silicones, sulphates are bad
They literally aren’t. All of these assumptions stem from half-baked, unscientific assumptions. Stop letting fear dictate your choices. 

3️⃣ Senseless buzzwords like “chemical-free” and “endocrine disruptors”
Everything, even water and air, are chemicals. You can literally die from too much water! The dose makes the poison. And no, our perfumes and fragranced products aren’t “disrupting your endocrine system”. lol. 

4️⃣ Thin = healthy
Thin doesn’t automatically mean healthy, and fat doesn’t automatically mean unhealthy. You can’t tell someone’s health status just by looking at their body. And even if someone’s not healthy, that doesn’t mean they deserve to be treated badly. 

5️⃣ Pores need to be shrunk as much as possible
No. Pores are literally a natural part of the skin’s anatomy. 

6️⃣ Women need to be married before 30
No one “needs” to be married by any particular age. And women in particular wre pushed to marry before 30 so that they’re trapped before they’ve gained enough life experience and cognitive development to see situations clearly and stand up for themselves. Don’t fall for it. Marriage isn’t a necessity, and if you do it, do it at the right time for the right reasons. 

7️⃣ Laying boundaries with elders = disrespect
Desi culture grants this absurd impunity to elders to do and say whatever they want, for some reason. Respect is a two-way street, and standing up for yourself when being mistreated isn’t disrespectful. 

8️⃣ “Gut health” influencers
While gut health is definitely an important aspect of overall health, I firmly believe that 99% of the gut health influencers are talking out of their asses and are not at all qualified to be giving people advice on this topic. 

#beautythreads #bodyacceptancemovement #guthealthcoach

No one does skincare like the Koreans 👏🏽

The Cato range from P.Calm is honestly so underrated, especially if your skin barrier needs some TLC.

The sunscreen is watery, lightweight, and packed with FOUR photostable UV filters 💧🛡️ Plus some really thoughtful extras like glutathione, ceramides, and lactobacillus ferment (a hallmark of K-beauty) for your barrier.

And the Cato Cream is a dream for anyone with a sensitive, damaged, or chronically dry skin barrier. It doesn’t just hydrate, it actually helps fix the root cause of the issue 🙌🏽

Honestly, if you’ve been curious about K-beauty, this is a great place to start. Both are available on @limese_connect 🧡💚

#pcalm #kbeautyskincareroutine #sensitiveskinsolution #koreansunscreen

Unsponsored review of the Raise Beauty On Cloud 9 ampoule to cream scalp and hair conditioner 👩🏻‍🦱

This seemed like a really interesting product when I saw @globalbeautyfinds review it, so I placed an order to see if it would work as well for my wavy/curly hair as it did for her straight hair. 

Unfortunately the answer is no 🥲

While it feels soothing and cooling for my itchy scalp (which is due to seborrheic dermatitis aka SD), it does feel a bit too creamy and causes my scalp to become oily a bit faster post wash. 

On the flip side, it’s not conditioning enough for my strands 🤷🏽‍♀️ 

Overall, at this luxury price point, it honestly did not feel worth it to me at all. I’ll still use it up as I don’t *hate* it, but I definitely wouldn’t repurchase it.
